SIMPLE: stamp
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stamp
<hw>Stamp</hw> <pr>(st⟦acr⟧mp)</pr> <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Stamped</conjf> <pr>(st⟦acr⟧mt ; 215)</pr>; <pos>p.
pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Stamping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>stampen</ets>; akin to LG. & D. <ets>stampen</ets>, G.
<ets>stampfen</ets>, OHG. <ets>stampf⟦omac⟧n</ets>, Dan.
<ets>stampe</ets>, Sw. <ets>stampa</ets>, Icel. <ets>stappa</ets>, G.
<ets>stampf</ets> a pestle and E. <ets>step</ets>. See <er>Step</er>,
<pos>v. i.</pos>, and cf. <er>Stampede</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
strike beat, or press forcibly with the bottom of the foot, or by
thrusting the foot downward.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He frets, he fumes, he stares, he <qex>stamps</qex> the
ground.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To bring down (the foot) forcibly on the ground or
floor; <as>as, he <ex>stamped</ex> his foot with rage</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To crush; to pulverize; specifically
<fld>(Metal.)</fld>, to crush by the blow of a heavy stamp, as ore in a
mill.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I took your sin, the calf which ye had made, and burnt it with
fire, and <qex>stamped</qex> it, and ground it very small.</q>
<rj><qau>Deut. ix. 21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To impress with some mark or figure; <as>as, to
<ex>stamp</ex> a plate with arms or initials</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Fig.: To impress; to imprint; to fix deeply; <as>as,
to <ex>stamp</ex> virtuous principles on the heart</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God . . . has <qex>stamped</qex> no original characters on our
minds wherein we may read his being.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To cut out, bend, or indent, as paper, sheet metal,
etc., into various forms, by a blow or suddenly applied pressure with a
stamp or die, etc.; to mint; to coin.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To put a stamp on, as for postage; <as>as, to
<ex>stamp</ex> a letter; to <ex>stamp</ex> a legal
document</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To stamp out</b></col>, <cd>to put an end to by sudden
and energetic action; to extinguish; <as>as, <ex>to stamp out</ex> a
rebellion</as>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stamp</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stamp
<hw>Stamp</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To strike; to beat; to
crush.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These cooks how they <qex>stamp</qex> and strain and grind.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To strike the foot forcibly downward.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But starts, exclaims, and <qex>stamps</qex>, and raves, and
dies.</q> <rj><qau>Dennis.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stamp</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stamp
<hw>Stamp</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of stamping, as
with the foot.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The which stamps; any instrument for making
impressions on other bodies, as a die.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>'T is gold so pure⟦br⟧
It can not bear the <qex>stamp</qex> without alloy.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The mark made by stamping; a mark imprinted; an
impression.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That sacred name gives ornament and grace,⟦br⟧
And, like his <qex>stamp</qex>, makes basest metals pass.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That which is marked; a thing stamped.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hanging a golden <qex>stamp</qex> about their necks.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <ety>[F. <ets>estampe</ets>, of German origin. See
<er>Stamp</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <def>A picture cut in wood or
metal, or made by impression; a cut; a plate.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At Venice they put out very curious <qex>stamps</qex> of the
several edifices which are most famous for their beauty and
magnificence.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>An official mark set upon things chargeable with a
duty or tax to government, as evidence that the duty or tax is paid;
<as>as, the <ex>stamp</ex> on a bill of exchange</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>A stamped or printed device,
usually paper, issued by the government at a fixed price, and required
by law to be affixed to, or stamped on, certain papers, as evidence that
the government dues are paid; <as>as, a postage <ex>stamp</ex>; a tax
<ex>stamp</ex>; a receipt <ex>stamp</ex>, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>An instrument for cutting out, or shaping,
materials, as paper, leather, etc., by a downward pressure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>A character or reputation, good or bad, fixed on
anything as if by an imprinted mark; current value; authority; <as>as,
these persons have the <ex>stamp</ex> of dishonesty; the Scriptures bear
the <ex>stamp</ex> of a divine origin</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of the same <qex>stamp</qex> is that which is obtruded on us, that
an adamant suspends the attraction of the loadstone.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T.
Browne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>Make; cast; form; character; <as>as, a man of the
same <ex>stamp</ex>, or of a different <ex>stamp</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A soldier of this season's <qex>stamp</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>A kind of heavy hammer, or pestle, raised by water
or steam power, for beating ores to powder; anything like a pestle, used
for pounding or beating.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>A half-penny.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Money, esp. paper money.</def>
<mark>[Slang, U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stamp act</b></col>, <cd>an act of the British Parliament
[1765] imposing a duty on all paper, vellum, and parchment used in the
American colonies, and declaring all writings on unstamped materials to
be null and void.</cd> -- <col><b>Stamp collector</b></col>,
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>an officer who receives or collects stamp duties.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>one who collects postage or other stamps, as an
avocation or for investment; a philatelist.</cd> -- <col><b>Stamp
duty</b></col>, <cd>a duty, or tax, imposed on paper and parchment used
for certain writings, as deeds, conveyances, etc., the evidence of the
payment of the duty or tax being a stamp.</cd> <mark>[Eng.]</mark> --
<col><b>Stamp hammer</b></col>, <cd>a hammer, worked by power, which
rises and falls vertically, like a stamp in a stamp mill.</cd> --
<col><b>Stamp head</b></col>, <cd>a heavy mass of metal, forming the
head or lower end of a bar, which is lifted and let fall, in a stamp
mill.</cd> -- <col><b>Stamp mill</b></col> <fld>(Mining)</fld>, <cd>a
mill in which ore is crushed with stamps; also, a machine for stamping
ore.</cd> -- <col><b>Stamp note</b></col>, <cd>a stamped certificate
from a customhouse officer, which allows goods to be received by the
captain of a ship as freight.</cd> <mark>[Eng.]</mark> -- <col><b>Stamp
office</b></col>, <cd>an office for the issue of stamps and the
reception of stamp duties.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stampede</ent>⟦br⟧
